Koalas¬†have had a rough gig lately with tens of thousands of individuals wiped out during the Black Summer bush fire season and ongoing logging of precious Koala habitat¬†means we're driving this national treasure to extinction.
We're at a critical point to secure the future of this beautiful species or they will go the way of the Tasmanian Tiger.

If you care about the future of our Koalas and want a fun, gentle way to share the message of their plight, I have created this important sticker pack you can use to show the world that we need to protect these animals.

This product is part of my Conservation Range and I will be donating 25% profit from this sticker pack to WIRES who provide funding and research to Koala focused groups on a national level along with providing a network of volunteers who rescue, rehabilitate and release Australian wildlife, including Koalas, every day.

Finally, an entire sticker pack dedicated to Surfing Koalas. In this pack you'll receive four awesome grey surfing legends who love nothing more than burying their chubby little grey bodies inside the belly of the world's fattest tubes.
The application possibilities of these little rippers are endless. Slap em' on your car, pop them on your phone, stick one on your laptop or even wear one proudly on your own surfboard.
These grey ledges are sure to please the most green of kooks and maybe even the GOAT himself.
Our new surfing koalas stickers are here and there are four of these beauties ready to be slapped onto surfboards, phones, car windows, drink bottles or wherever you'd like to stick them.
In Edition #2 of the Aussie Icons pack, we bring you another four fresh stickers that are more Aussie than a tree of Galahs.
This sticker pack includes four unmistakably Aussie icons including a Bunnings Snag, a Kookaburra, Vegemite and a Bubble-o-Bill.

A wildlife calendar for 2023 featuring some of Brent's most iconic illustrations and covering very important wildlife related dates like the beginning of magpie swooping season, Kookaburra awareness day, wombat appreciation day, world whale day, Earth hour, save the koala day, world oceans day and many more.

Please note, there's a small print fault where some artworks are mirrored. The calendar still looks great,¬†the most noticeable is in the July month where Sydney¬†opera house¬†is on the right side (oops) 🙃 We've reduced the price to reflect this.

Follow the sun and wake up to the sound of kookaburras laughing on Arakwal Country (Byron Bay), surf giant tubes with a crowd of noisy cockatoos on Yugambeh Country (Surfer‚Äôs Paradise), watch red-tailed black cockatoos fly over Anangu Country (Uluru) and go to sleep under the stars with Quokkas on Whadjuk Noongar Country (Rottnest Island).
Welcome to Australia as you've never seen it before: a dreamy pastel-popping ode to the significant places and animals on the land we all call home.
